textDisplay:
Hello. Just my ideas on your question & suggestions:

a) Hot or cool: Probably doesn't matter too much but letting them cool will allow the starch to set. This may make it easier to get most of the potato out.
b) Grated cheese: Maybe a little as seasoning and grated very fine. Add too much and you risk a problem at the frying step.
c) Parsley: Great idea but make sure it's very fine & well mixed in so that, when you do the egg/breadcrumb step, you get a perfect covering and your parsley doesn't burn when you fry.

Just my thoughts!
textOriginal:
Hello.  Just my ideas on your question & suggestions:

a) Hot or cool: Probably doesn't matter too much but letting them cool will allow the starch to set.  This may make it easier to get most of the potato out.
b) Grated cheese: Maybe a little as seasoning and grated very fine.  Add too much and you risk a problem at the frying step.
c) Parsley: Great idea but make sure it's very fine & well mixed in so that, when you do the egg/breadcrumb step, you get a perfect covering and your parsley doesn't burn when you fry.

Just my thoughts!

textDisplay:
I like the double fry method. In my experience you need to do 2 deep fries for crispy fries, the first fry precooks and draws moisture out to the outside where it is evaporated off in the second deep fry. Here is what I use to get Mcdonalds French Fries at home

The way I get crispy fries similar to Mcdonald's:

1) Cut them thin and soak them first in cold water for at least an hour up to 4 hours to get the starch out, ice water is best. You can tell they are good when the water runs clear when you rinse them

2)While they are soaking the last bit bring a pot of water to a boil with some white sugar and corn syrup in it

3)After they have soaked in the ice water turn OFF the boiling sugar water and transfer your fries into that for 5 minutes to pre cook and give them that extra flavour most people are missing in their home fries.

4)After 5 minutes in the shut off water take them out and pat them dry, at this point you can freeze them for later use or cook them right away. (I always do a ten pound bag of Russets all at once and freeze the leftovers for later use then make more after those run out.)

5) To COOK them you need to do 2 SEPARATE deep fries this is essential for crispy fries at home, the ones Mcdonalds gets in the store have had all of this done to them up until that point so they only need 1 cook in store

6)2 minutes in 350-375 oil (I have a little deep fryer so I leave it on 375 to try and keep the temp up) then take them out and let them cool until they are cool to the touch, it is beneficial to pat off the oil and moisture that seeps out as this point but a lot of the time I don't for the mess and to save paper towel.

7) After they have cooled back into the same temp oil for 5-7 minutes depending how thick you cut them


Some tips for the best fries:


1)Russets are best

2)Cut them thinner than you think you need to if you like them like Mcdonalds/thin, I always used to think they will be too thin but you figure it out after a few times

3)If they are not staying crispy after you cook them that is probably because your oil is too old/dirty. NEW oil is best for crispiness and USED oil adds more flavour to your fries, the BEST fries at a Mcdonalds are not right after they change the oil but they are the crispiest. The BEST fries are about 1-2 days after its been changed depending how busy it's been, they are still crispy but have more flavor.


Good luck if you try it out let me know, also freezing them draws even more moisture out so fries that you have frozen are even better than fresh.

textDisplay: You can't just substitute white grape juice for white wine because it is way too sweet, so I would make a white wine substitute in this way: 1. Replace the quantity of white wine with half that quantity of additional chicken stock and the other half with water.  2. to this mixture, add two teaspoons of white wine vinegar.  3. stir in tiny bits of sugar and dissolve them thoroughly before tasting; add just enough such that the flavor doesn't scream "VINEGAR!" alone.  This should give you a Halal substitute for white wine.  I did a good bit of study on the Halal dietary laws and used a Muslim Groceries Guide that was very detailed so that we could properly entertain a Muslim friend of ours many years ago, and the consensus at the time was that the Imams had declared vinegars (and, by extension, alegars) to no longer be considered Haram because there was no wine remaining, only acetic acid and water (and natural flavorings, as is the case with apple cider vinegar, red wine vinegar, etc).  If this determination is no longer valid then please let me know.  Peace be with you, brother.
textOriginal: You can't just substitute white grape juice for white wine because it is way too sweet, so I would make a white wine substitute in this way: 1. Replace the quantity of white wine with half that quantity of additional chicken stock and the other half with water.  2. to this mixture, add two teaspoons of white wine vinegar.  3. stir in tiny bits of sugar and dissolve them thoroughly before tasting; add just enough such that the flavor doesn't scream "VINEGAR!" alone.  This should give you a Halal substitute for white wine.  I did a good bit of study on the Halal dietary laws and used a Muslim Groceries Guide that was very detailed so that we could properly entertain a Muslim friend of ours many years ago, and the consensus at the time was that the Imams had declared vinegars (and, by extension, alegars) to no longer be considered Haram because there was no wine remaining, only acetic acid and water (and natural flavorings, as is the case with apple cider vinegar, red wine vinegar, etc).  If this determination is no longer valid then please let me know.  Peace be with you, brother.
